04361nmm a2200697Ia 9781479876730DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798767307 a10.18574/nyu/9781479899623.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548131  a(OCoLC)896872932  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a172.109731 aBender, Steven W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMea Culpa :bLessons on Law and Regret from U.S. History /cSteven W. Bender. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Mea Culpa, Steven W. Bender examines how the United States’ collective shame about its past has shaped the evolution of law and behavior. We regret slavery and segregationist Jim Crow laws. We eventually apologize, while ignoring other oppressions, and our legal response to regret often fails to be transformative for the affected groups. By examining policies and practices that have affected the lives ofgroups that have been historically marginalized and oppressed, Bender is able to draw persuasive connections between shame and its eventual legalmanifestations. Analyzing the United States’ historical response to its own atrocities, Bender identifies and develops a definitive moral compass thatguides us away from the policies and practices that lead to societal regret.Mea Culpa challenges its readers. In a different era, might we have been slave owners or proprietors of a racially segregated establishment? It’s easy to judge immorality in the hindsight of history, but what current practices and policies will later generations regret?More than a historical survey, this volume offers a framework for resolving some of the most contentious socialproblems of our time. Drawing on his background as a legal scholar, Bender tackles immigration, the death penalty, the war on terror, reproductive rights,welfare, wage inequity, homelessness, mass incarceration, and same-sex marriage. Ultimately, he argues, it is the dehumanization of human beings thatallows for practices to occur that will later be marked as regrettable. And all of us have a stake in standing on the side of history that resists dehumanization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aDiscriminationxLaw and legislationxHistoryxUnited States. 0aDiscriminationxLaw and legislationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aHuman rightsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aHuman rightszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMarginality, SocialxPolitical aspectsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aMarginality, SocialxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMinoritiesxLegal status, laws, etcxHistoryxUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxLegal status, laws, etczUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMinoritiesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRegretxPolitical aspectsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aRegretxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479899623.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479876730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479876730/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles